{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://spokenweb.github.io/Ultimatumi1985/manifests/alan-lord-at-ultimatum-festival-1985-05-01.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"en":["Alan Lord at Ultimatum Festival 1985-05-01"]},"homepage":[{"id":"https://spokenweb.github.io/Ultimatumi1985","type":"Text","label":{"en":["Alan Lord at Ultimatum Festival 1985-05-01"]},"format":"text/html"}],"metadata":[{"label":{"en":["Description"]},"value":{"en":["The following is a transcription of Alan Lord’s performance at Ultimatum I, Wednesday, May 1st, 1985 at the Foufounes Electriques. Alan Lord is the festival organizer and creator of Ultimatum. He is a Canadian musician, writer and engineer, and was a member of the bands Vex, the Marauders, Vent du Mont Scharr and Alan Lord & the Falling Men. An important figure for Montreal’s alternative punk scene, he is featured in Erik Cimon’s documentary \"Mtl Punk -- The first wave\" (2011). During his Ultimatum set, he performed four song-poems, including \"Ignoring the Future Today'' and \"Too Much Money\" with accompanying electronic music tapes by Jean-Luc Bonspiel and computer graphics videos done by Boris Wanowitch. The Ultimatum LP features “Ignore the Future Today” with music by Jean-Luc Bonspiel and words and vocals by Alan Lord. \n"]}},{"label":{"en":["Language"]},"value":{"en":["English"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://spokenweb.github.io/Ultimatumi1985/alan_lord_at_ultimatum_festival_1985_05_01/canvas/5","type":"Canvas","duration":1016,"annotations":[{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://spokenweb.github.io/Ultimatumi1985/manifests/alan_lord_at_ultimatum_festival_1985_05_01-canvas5-1","type":"AnnotationPage","label":{"en":["Default"]},"items":[{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","type":"Annotation","motivation":["commenting","tagging"],"id":"https://spokenweb.github.io/Ultimatumi1985/alan_lord_at_ultimatum_festival_1985_05_01/canvas/5/page1","body":[{"type":"Te